        <td bgcolor="black" colspan="2"  valign="top">
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;10/05/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 18:43:26</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=3874"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
 
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=3874')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=TopicQuote&amp;TOPIC_ID=9343&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Dots+vs+DD%27s+%2D+is+there+balance%3F"><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"> Posted this on the FoH boards in response to a post made by yaguex regarding our upcoming PoP spells.  Basically as i see it, VI needs to review and inspect the current balance and relationship between dots and dd's and provide some tweaks to better balance classes like the necromancer class.</P><P>Hopefully, someone from VI may read this post, see some logical explainations of how and why dots should be balanced and implement them for us either prior to or in conjunction with the release of PoP.</P><P>This post isnt necessarily a jab at PoP, but more so a plea to VI to review dot balance and affectuate some changes in order to better balance our class.</P><P>~~~~~~</P><P>EQ is a inter-related system of give and takes and in theory, dots should provide superior damage due to the time it takes to inflict its damage. It only makes logical sense that at some point in time, necro's should exceed every other casting class in terms of casting damage due to what should be a superiority in the dmg efficiency of dots. Unfortunately, i think VI has really f'd up with the relationship of dots vs dd's and this problem is only further exagerated with the PoP expansion. Lets consider a few examples to illustrate my point: </P><P><b>Bane of Thule vs Sunstrike</b><BR>Consider this fact, bane of thule, a lvl 61 necro PoP spell inflicts approximately 1600 dmg for 425 mana for a ratio of 3.76. Sunstrike inflicts approximately 1600 dmg for 450 mana for a ratio of 3.55. Now consider the fact that BoT takes 42 seconds to deliver its full dmg where as sunstrike is instant. Also consider the fact that BoT draws tremendous agro (assuming it follows suit for all poison based dots) where as sunstrike doesnt. So when comparing these, can someone please justify why Bane of thule does about the same dmg for only 25 less mana and 10x the agro???? Also, lets not forget, BoT is conjuration based, where sunstrike is evoc based. Necro's wont receive specialization and AA mana savers when casting this dot. </P><P><b>Funeral Pyre vs Garrison's Superior Sundering</b> <BR>Now lets consider funeral pyre vs Garrison's Superior Sundering. Consider the fact that dots cant crit and dd's can. Lets assume an instance where a wizzie and a necro both have 60 aa points, with the wizzie investing his into casting fury and casting fury mastery (crit's at 20 percent not counting innate crits). Lets say each caster casts his respective spell 100 times. Disregarding specialization checks (assuming its a wash here) and disregarding focus items (which in fact favor the wizzie) a wizzie will have spent 54000 mana to do 252,000 dmg for a ratio of 4.66. </P><P>Now if the necromancer casts funeral pyre 100 times, considering the fact he cant crit, will have done 216,000dmg for 45000mana for a ratio of 4.8. Is there proper balance when garrison's can provide 95% of the mana efficiency of the most powerful dot in game? Especially considering the fact that each necro is limited to one application of funeral pyre at any moment in time and is limited by the number of buff slots available on a mob? </P><P>I could go on and on with these illustrations but wont for the sake of not creating a thesis on the subject matter. However, my point is - dot efficiency must be looked into. For better dot balance, i would recommend the following as solutions: <BR>- All necro dots (save our lifetap dots)must have a minimum mana to dmg ratio of 4.5 to 1 and should have a cap around 6.5 to 1. Dots delivering a 4.5 ratio should have the benefit of delivering high dps (40+ dps) and the superior mana/dmg dots should provide much lower dps (15-25dps) but at the benefit of gaining mana efficiency. Basically set a sliding scale to balance mana/dmg ratio's vs dot dps. </P><P>- All dots save splurt should have a 10-15 percent reduction in mana costs -- or -- allow for the lich and clarity lines to stack </P><P>- Implement Dot fury and dot fury mastery in order to better balance dots vrs dd's. </P><P>- Provide necro's with a cold based dot line. Its extremely crippling dmg wise when a mob is immune to a major dot line of a dotting class. Wizzies, mages and druids (the dd classes) experience minor effects to their dps if a mob is immune to one of their dd lines (aka they can switch to another dd line) where as for necro's, it reduces their potential dmg dramatically (aka AoW is immune to fire and significantly limits a nec's dmg output because of the loss of 58 dps from funeral pyre and pyrocur). Yes it can be argued that nec's can use plague, ebolt or cessation of cor to compensate, however, for anyone that has played the class will fully understand why this is not a feasible alternative. Poison and disease dots are extremely difficult to land on fully debuffed boss mobs and all carry outragous agro which generally result in getting summoned and killed (which is why i never cast these). </P><P>- Increase the number of buff slots on a mob from 30 to 60. As it stands now, for most raid encounters, buff slot real-estate isnt an issue. However, with the growing number of dots entering the game and with the growing number of debuffs entering the game, 30 slots will become far too slots for lets say 4 nec's, 3 shammy's and 4 druids to fully apply their dots given all the debuffs that are expected to be applied. </P><P>I'm sure i'll get flamed for this post, as someone is bound to say - well necro's can solo (so can just about any other class in eq), or necro's have pets (which do minimal dmg on high end mobs) or necro's have all those utility spells (which arent really needed in raid situations - due to an abundance of buff/debuff specialists) but imo i've listed what should be modified with regards to necro dots in order to better balance themselves relative to dd's.</P><P>I just ask VI to ask themselves the following question. Given the current relationships of dots vs dd's is there a proper risk/reward or cost/benefit relationship established for dots considering the limitations associated with them (aka time, slots, immunities, etc...)?</P><P>Tencor Laureate - 60th Warlock<BR><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=55675" target="_blank">My Profile</a><BR><a href="http://www.veilofsilence.org" target="_blank">Veil of Silence</a> <BR>Innoruuk Server</font></td>

      </tr>

